---
import EditorLayout from '../layouts/EditorLayout.astro';
import { loadProjects } from '../lib/projects';

const projects = loadProjects();
const projectList = projects.map((p) => ({ slug: p.slug, title: p.title }));
---

<EditorLayout
  title="Kevin's Lab"
  currentTab="readme.md"
  projects={projectList}
>
  <h1>Kevin's Lab</h1>

  <p>
    This site is a <strong>dev log</strong> of my projects. I use it to document what I'm building with quick notes and ideas I jot down while working—think of it as a scratchpad that happens to live on the web.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Don't expect much in terms of content.</strong> You'll mostly find rough notes, half-baked thoughts, and snippets. There may be mistakes, typos, or outdated bits. That's by design: this is where I capture ideas in the moment, not polished docs.
  </p>

  <h2>How it's organized</h2>

  <p>
    Each section is laid out like a normal text editor. Under <strong>PROJECTS</strong> in the sidebar you'll see folders—one per project. Open a folder to find the notes for that project. Each project can contain:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Notes</strong> — markdown files with my dev log entries</li>
    <li><strong>Photos</strong> — images I drop in while building</li>
    <li><strong>3D models</strong> — assets and references for hardware or design work</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    So if you're poking around a project, you might see a mix of text, images, and 3D viewers, depending on what I've added.
  </p>

  <h2>Work-related stuff</h2>

  <p>
    There's a separate section in the sidebar for <strong>Work</strong>—résumé, portfolio links, and other career-related info. If you're here for that, switch to the Work view in the activity bar on the left.
  </p>

  <hr />

  <p>
    <a href="/dashboard">Dashboard</a> — stats and active projects overview.
  </p>
</EditorLayout>
